Pre-processing

# assign descriptive column names where absent
names(data.raw)[1]<-"germ"

# remove non-needed columns
data.trunc <- data.raw[-1,c(1,2,4:7,9:11)]
## Alternatively, use notes <- grep(pattern="note", x=names(data.trunc), ignore.case=TRUE)
##names(data.trunc)[notes] # double check we got the right columns
##data.trunc <- subset(data.trunc, select = -notes) # apply filter.

# function to remove percent signs
dropPct<-function(df, var){
  dropPct<-strsplit(as.character(df[[var]]), split="%")
  df[[var]]<-as.numeric(dropPct)
  return(df[[var]])
}

# remove % signs from 2nd col, leaving a numeric value.
data.trunc[["case.fatality.rate"]]<-dropPct(data.trunc, "case.fatality.rate")

Check for missing data

# coerce 3rd col into numeric form
data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate <- as.numeric(as.character(data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate))
##Alternatively, use as.numeric(levels(data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate))[data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate]
## (see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3418128/how-to-convert-a-factor-to-an-integer-numeric-without-a-loss-of-information )

# check for missing data in our 2 numeric columns of interest
c("Missing values for case fatality rate: ", sum(is.na(data.trunc$case.fatality.rate)))
## [1] "Missing values for case fatality rate: "
## [2] "0"
c("Missing values for reproductive rate: ", sum(is.na(data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate)))
## [1] "Missing values for reproductive rate: "
## [2] "1"
# average.basic.reproductive.rate has one NA value. find it
which(is.na(data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate))
## [1] 1
# the primary mode of transmission column is a factor. looking at the data, there are missing values that are just blanks
str(data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission)
##  Factor w/ 9 levels "","airborne",..: 1 3 4 6 7 3 1 4 5 6 ...
# get the number and location of missing data in 3rd column
sum((as.character(data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission))=="")
## [1] 2
which((as.character(data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission))=="")
## [1] 1 7

As it turns out, the row with an NA value for average.basic.reproductive.rate also has missing data for the 3rd column. So rows 1 and 7 are the problem data

Checking for problematic data

Now check the case fatality rate and average basic reproductive rate to see if there is problematic data.

Firstly, case.fatality.rate is a percentage, so check to see if there are any obvious errors.

c( min(data.trunc$case.fatality.rate), max(data.trunc$case.fatality.rate) )
## [1]   0 100

Seems fine, so we move on to average basic reproductive rate.

#preliminary visualization of average.basic.reproductive.rate
boxplot(data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate)

#seems like there's an outlier, find the row of interest
which((data.trunc$average.basic.reproductive.rate)>=70)
## [1] 17

data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission[6] <- "food"

Futher data cleaning

Look at the transmission categories again.

table(data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission) 
## 
##                          airborne airborne droplet            bites 
##                0                1               14                6 
##      body fluids       fecal-oral             food   sexual contact 
##                4                5                3                3 
##         surfaces 
##                2

It seems like airborne and airborne droplets should be the same category. Since there is only one entry for airborne, we can find that row and change it.

which((data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission)== "airborne")
## [1] 17
data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission[17] <- "airborne droplet"

If we use the table() function on this column again, we find that airborne has not completely gone away. We forgot to coerce the column from factor to characters.

data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission <- as.character(data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission)
table(data.trunc$primary.mode.of.transmission)
## 
## airborne droplet            bites      body fluids       fecal-oral 
##               15                6                4                5 
##             food   sexual contact         surfaces 
##                3                3                2

Saving the data

save(data.trunc, file = "Microbes_cleaned.Rdata")
load("Microbes_cleaned.Rdata")

Drawing the graph

p<- ggplot(data.trunc, aes(x=average.basic.reproductive.rate, y=case.fatality.rate, colour=primary.mode.of.transmission)) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 1, colour="black", size=1) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(5,7,12), colour="grey", size=1, alpha=.5) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, colour="black", size=1) +
  annotate("rect", xmin=-Inf, xmax=Inf, ymin=0, ymax=1, fill="grey40", alpha=0.1) +
  annotate("rect", xmin=-Inf, xmax=Inf, ymin=20, ymax=50, fill="grey40", alpha=0.1) +
  geom_point(size = 5) +
  geom_text(aes(label = germ), hjust=-.11, vjust=.5, angle=8) +
  scale_y_continuous(name="DEADLINESS (case fatility rate)", limit=c(0, 100), breaks= seq(0,100,10), minor_breaks=NULL) +     
  scale_x_continuous(name="CONTAGIOUSNESS (no of people one person will likely infect)", breaks= seq(0,17,1), minor_breaks=NULL) +
  labs(title="The Microbe-scope") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(colour="grey", linetype = "dotted"), plot.margin = unit(c(3,8,4,1), "lines"), legend.direction = "horizontal", legend.position = c(.8,1.06), plot.title= element_text(size=24, face="bold", vjust=5, hjust=0))

#replicate the annotations
p1<- p + annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="not very"), xmax=1, ymin=110) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="quite contagious"), xmin=1, xmax=5, ymin=110) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="very"), xmin=5, xmax=7, ymin=110) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="highly"), xmin=7, xmax=12, ymin=110) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="vaccinate now!"), xmin=12, xmax=17, ymin=110) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="extremely deadly"), xmin=21, ymin=50, ymax=100) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="deadly"), xmin=21, ymin=20, ymax=50) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="quite deadly"), xmin=21, ymin=1, ymax=20) +
  annotation_custom(grob=textGrob(label="R0 = 1 \n disease not \n likely to spread"), xmin=1, xmax=3, ymax=-25)

#remove clipping so data labels and the words outside the graph area will show
gt <- ggplot_gtable(ggplot_build(p1))
gt$layout$clip[gt$layout$name=="panel"] <- "off"
grid.draw(gt)
